### 10. Update Program.cs

Add `IDbContextFactory` registration. Replace the `AddDbContext` line with `AddDbContextFactory`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<ApplicationDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlite(connectionString));
```

Also keep `AddDbContext` for Identity (Identity needs it). Actually, `AddDbContextFactory` also registers the `DbContext` in the DI container. But Identity specifically uses `AddDbContext`. The correct approach is to keep `AddDbContext` AND also add `AddDbContextFactory`. Wait - in .NET 8+, `AddDbContextFactory` registers both the factory AND the DbContext. But Identity uses `AddEntityFrameworkStores<ApplicationDbContext>()` which resolves `ApplicationDbContext` from DI.

The safest approach: Change `AddDbContext` to `AddDbContextFactory` — this registers both the factory and the scoped DbContext service.

Replace:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContext<ApplicationDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlite(connectionString));
```

With:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<ApplicationDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlite(connectionString));
```

Also add auto-migration before `app.Run()`:

```csharp
using (var scope = app.Services.CreateScope())
{
    var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<ApplicationDbContext>();
    db.Database.Migrate();
}
```

And also disable confirmed account requirement so testing is easier (change `options.SignIn.RequireConfirmedAccount = true` to `false`).

### 11. Ensure Auth Required Everywhere

The Home page already has `[Authorize]`. All other pages (Patients, Appointments, Billing) have `[Authorize]`. Additionally, add a fallback authorization policy to Program.cs:

After `builder.Services.AddRazorComponents()...` add:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthorizationBuilder()
    .SetFallbackPolicy(new Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization.AuthorizationPolicyBuilder()
        .RequireAuthenticatedUser()
        .Build());
```

Wait, this may interfere with Identity pages (login, register need to be anonymous). The Identity pages use `[AllowAnonymous]` so the fallback policy approach should be fine. Actually, let me check — the scaffolded Identity pages should already have `[AllowAnonymous]`. Yes they do. So adding a fallback policy is the correct approach.

### Execution

Please implement ALL of these steps. After implementing, run `dotnet build` to verify everything compiles. If there are build errors, fix them.

Also delete the Counter.razor, Weather.razor, and Auth.razor files.

After everything builds successfully, create an AGENTS.md file in the project root with the server-global template content (replacing {AppName} with VetClinic) and an additional Authentication section noting that ASP.NET Core Identity is configured.

