### 10. Update Program.cs

Add `IDbContextFactory` registration. Replace the `AddDbContext` line with `AddDbContextFactory`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<ApplicationDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlite(connectionString));
```

Also keep `AddDbContext` for Identity (Identity needs it). Actually, `AddDbContextFactory` also registers the `DbContext` in the DI container. But Identity specifically uses `AddDbContext`. The correct approach is to keep `AddDbContext` AND also add `AddDbContextFactory`. Wait - in .NET 8+, `AddDbContextFactory` registers both the factory AND the DbContext. But Identity uses `AddEntityFrameworkStores<ApplicationDbContext>()` which resolves `ApplicationDbContext` from DI.

The safest approach: Change `AddDbContext` to `AddDbContextFactory` — this registers both the factory and the scoped DbContext service.

Replace:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContext<ApplicationDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlite(connectionString));
```

With:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<ApplicationDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlite(connectionString));
```

Also add auto-migration before `app.Run()`:

```csharp
using (var scope = app.Services.CreateScope())
{
    var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<ApplicationDbContext>();
    db.Database.Migrate();
}
```

And also disable confirmed account requirement so testing is easier (change `options.SignIn.RequireConfirmedAccount = true` to `false`).

